long_desc.thetext:
Created attachment 1177865 screenshot of white/ blank background
Description of problem: Install f24
Version-Release number of selected component (if applicable): $ rpm -qa gnome-shell gnome-shell-3.20.3-1.fc24.x86_64
How reproducible: More often than not, but intermitant
Steps to Reproduce: 1. Install f24 2. Login to user account 3.
Actual results: White background
Expected results: Pretty background
Additional info: See attached screenshot
Having same problem. Half of OS boots - background normal, other half white.
Can confirm - happens also for me.

Same problem with gnome-shell-3.20.3-3.fc24.x86_64 on Asus UX305UA-FC057T with screen size 1980x1080
I have gnome-tweak-tool-3.20.1-1.fc24.noarch and "Icons on Desktop" is enable.
When I start session I get white background.
If using gnome-tweak-tool I switch "Icons on Desktop" to disable I get the default background.
After that I can switch back "Icons on Desktop" to enable with no problem.
Did somebody have a look on this bug opened since 2016-07-09 ?

For me fixed by Nautilus 3.20.2 available in testing
What's new in Nautilus 3.20.2 July 29th, 2016
Fix white desktop background after changing themes (Sebastien Keller) Improve double click detection (Johannes Oertel) Fix path bar menu on wayland appearing on random places (Olivier Fourdan) Only save zoom level if the level has changed (Mike Gorse) Fix date difference calculation for attributes like Modified Date (Ernestas Kulik) Hide floating bar on hover (Carlos Soriano) Fix detection of remote systems for not thumbnailing (Ernestas Kulik) Fix sorting on Japanese locale (Ernestas Kulik) Fix gnome shell search provider not being recursive (Carlos Soriano) Fix copy operation lags (Razvan Chitu) Avoid unresponsiveness when file chooser is opened (Ernestas Kulik) Fix renaming duplicated logic on search and recent (Ernestas Kulik) Fix trash handling to delete files if disk is full (Mario Sanchez Prada)
Read more: http://linux.softpedia.com/progChangelog/Nautilus-Changelog-4532.html

I'll assume that all affected people have desktop icons enabled, and that the issue is therefore fixed by the nautilus update. Please reopen if the assumption is wrong and you can reproduce the issue without desktop icons.
